**Current API surface:**
```C#
    public partial struct JsonReaderState
    {
        public JsonReaderState(int maxDepth = 64, JsonReaderOptions options = default) { throw null; }
        public long BytesConsumed { get { throw null; } }
        public int MaxDepth { get { throw null; } }
        public System.Text.Json.JsonReaderOptions Options { get { throw null; } }
        public System.SequencePosition Position { get { throw null; } }
    }
```

See https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/35245#discussion_r255734973

> But we should really examine what's necessary to live on JsonReaderState and what doesn't have to.

> Looks like this would shave 24 bytes off of a JsonReaderState, which means 24 bytes off of every state machine it's stored in that ends up on the heap.

We could reduce the size of `JsonReaderState` if we remove `BytesConsumed` and `SequencePosition` from it. These properties are not retained when passed to a new instance of `Utf8JsonReader` and hence are not needed by the reader to continue partial reads.

The main benefit of keeping them on the `JsonReaderState` is that the caller doesn't have to grab these properties from the `Utf8JsonReader` explicitly. For example, when reading from a `PipeReader`, the method that creates the `Utf8JsonReader` and tracks it state, only needs to return the `JsonReaderState` back to the caller. If we remove these properties from the state, the method would need to return the `SequencePosition` as well.

The downside of keeping the `JsonReaderState` unchanged is higher heap allocation since the state survives across the await.

**Current:**
```C#
ReadResult result = await _pipe.Reader.ReadAsync();
ReadOnlySequence<byte> data = result.Buffer;
// ProcessData contains the ref struct Utf8JsonReader, grabs the state before returning
state = ProcessData(data, isFinalBlock, state); 
_pipe.Reader.AdvanceTo(state.Position);

private static JsonReaderState ProcessData(ReadOnlySequence<byte> ros, bool isFinalBlock, JsonReaderState state = default)
{
    var json = new Utf8JsonReader(ros, isFinalBlock, state);
    while (json.Read())
    {
        //...
    }
    return json.CurrentState;
}
```

**If we remove these properties from the `JsonReaderState`:**
```C#
ReadResult result = await _pipe.Reader.ReadAsync();
ReadOnlySequence<byte> data = result.Buffer;
// ProcessData contains the ref struct Utf8JsonReader, grabs the state, but also needs to grab the position property to know how much to advance
(state, pos) = ProcessData(data, isFinalBlock, state);
_pipe.Reader.AdvanceTo(pos);

private static (JsonReaderState, SequencePosition) ProcessData(ReadOnlySequence<byte> ros, bool isFinalBlock, JsonReaderState state = default)
{
    var json = new Utf8JsonReader(ros, isFinalBlock, state);
    while (json.Read())
    {
        //...
    }
    return (json.CurrentState, json.Position);
}
```

cc @stephentoub, @bartonjs, @pakrym, @steveharter, @davidfowl, @KrzysztofCwalina

